luded from events and projects, or, if you were on a project you are routinely phased out of it so that the "managers" can receive the "glory" associated with a "job well done." I experienced more than one occasion where I was intentionally left out of meetings on projects I had been working on.Other cons:Expressly forbidden from speaking to upper management. Criticized for providing honest, diplomatic feedback about a project. Retaliated against for being ill. Given menial projects when requesting more work because I had capacity, while managers complained to everyone who would listen about how busy they were.The culture is horrible. You are made fun of, discriminated against and harassed, albeit quietly sometimes and more overtly at other times.I have never reviewed a former company before but feel so strongly that Global Atlantic is headed in the wrong direction (and opening themselves up to countless lawsuits with the way management speaks to employees -- with ZERO concern for HR rules and regulations) that I had to post.Advice to ManagementStop thinking you are the be all/end all of management. You have smart people working for you and you treat them like children. Get some management training. Get some sensitivity training. Don't threaten to take away a promotion because someone gets sick, and don't tell your employees you won't hire women anymore because all they do is get pregnant and go on maternity leave.Share on FacebookShare on TwitterShare on WhatsAppShare via EmailCopy LinkLink Copied!Flag as InappropriateFlag as InappropriateHelpful (5) Global Atlantic Financial Group Response seconds agoEdit • Delete Global Atlantic Financial Group 2016-09-09 12:27 PDT Jul 10, 2016 Helpful (7)"Difficult Environment"StarStarStarStarStarWork/Life BalanceCulture & ValuesCareer OpportunitiesComp & BenefitsSenior ManagementFormer Employee - Finance in Southborough, MAFormer Employee - Finance in Southborough, MADoesn't RecommendNeutral OutlookProsThe company pays well. Th